<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-650-865  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 650 865.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Dec 3 1990 n329 p4(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New York gets MFS; more access for the financial district.andO;(Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc.) (includes a related article onNew York's reaction to alternative access telecommunicationsservices)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schwartz, Jeffrey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc (MFS) introduces its dedicatedlocal-access services in New York that give downtown financialdistrict users an alternative local-access-service provider.andP;  MFSis also installing transmission equipment and fiber connections to27 office buildings in lower Manhattan.andP;  Users welcome MFS andbelieve that having another service provider in New York willbring about lower rates through increased price competition.andP;  Theservice also provides businesses with another alternative fordisaster recovery planning, assuring a safer telecommunicationsinfrastructure throughout New York City.andP;  MFS has installed 1,800miles of fiber in lower Manhattan and is currently installing itsdigital transmission and fiber optic network facilities throughoutManhattan and the other New York City boroughs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc. (Services).andO;Topic:     CompetitionTelephone CompaniesCommunications Service SuppliersNew YorkTelecommunications Services.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>